\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
An alternative model with sorting and selection for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Migration, Specialization, and Trade: Evidence from the Brazilian March
 to the West
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by Brian Cevallos Fujiy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
An alternative model with sorting and selection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is an alternative model to the knowledge diffusion contained in Pellegrina
 + Sotelo (mimeo).
 The idea is that it is possible that the positive correlation between migration
 flows 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{ijkt}$
\end_inset

 and amount of people at the origin region 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{ik,t-1}$
\end_inset

 is generated by more productive farmers moving towards XXX.
 In this section we consider such case based on Behrens et al (2014).
 Now the model.
 There is a fixed amount of people in Brazil 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1$
\end_inset

.
 Each farmer from origin region 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 chooses its destination 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, and once is there, it choose which crop 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to grow.
 All farmers are exante identical, except for their talent 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and serendipity 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Each farmers initially knows its talent, then choose where to migrate.
 After moving, serendipity happens.
 Talent times serendipity determines the farmer's productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=t\times s$
\end_inset

.
 Knowing its productivity allows the farmer to select which crop to farm.
 The number of regions 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is discrete and fixed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Selection and Agglomeration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before dealing with sorting, we deal with selection given that location
 sorting has already been made.
 This is where the most important of the analysis is anyway since here is
 where agglomeration forces appear.
 Consider some region.
 People now discover their serendipity, then they know their productivity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 After their discover their productivity, they decide which crop to grow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each farmer produces a variety 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 of the crop 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The demand for that variety comes from a representative consumer maximizing
 utility subject to its budget constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max\quad U=(\sum_{k}(\int_{\Omega_{k}}q_{k}(\omega)^{\frac{{\epsilon_{k}-1}}{\epsilon_{k}}})^{\frac{{\epsilon_{k}}}{\epsilon_{k}-1}\frac{{\sigma-1}}{\sigma}})^{\frac{{\sigma}}{\sigma-1}}\qquad s.t.\qquad\sum_{k}\int_{\Omega_{k}}q_{k}(\omega)p_{k}(\omega)\leq X$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Notice that the elasticity of substitution across varieties for a given
 crop depends on the crop itself.
 This generates demand:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $q_{k}(\omega)=(\frac{{p_{k}(\omega)}}{p_{k}})^{-\epsilon_{k}}(\frac{{p_{k}}}{p})^{-\sigma}q$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p=(\sum_{k}p_{k}^{1-\sigma})^{\frac{{1}}{1-\sigma}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}=(\int_{\Omega_{k}}p_{k}(\omega)^{1-\epsilon_{k}}d\omega)^{\frac{{1}}{1-\epsilon_{k}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The farmer that grows variety 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 of a crop 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 maximizes profits subject to its demand:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $max\quad\Pi_{k}(\omega)=(p_{k}(\omega)-\frac{{c_{k}}}{\phi_{k}(\omega)A_{k}})q_{k}(\omega)\qquad s.t.\qquad q_{k}(\omega)=(\frac{{p_{k}(\omega)}}{p_{k}})^{-\epsilon_{k}}(\frac{{p_{k}}}{p})^{-\sigma}q$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}$
\end_inset

 are unit costs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{k}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is productivity, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{k}$
\end_inset

 is crop-productivity.
 Then, we get a price function that depends on a constant markup and unit
 costs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}(\omega)=(\frac{{\epsilon_{k}}}{\epsilon_{k}-1})\frac{{c_{k}}}{\phi_{k}(\omega)A_{k}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Then, aggregated prices are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}=(\frac{{\epsilon_{k}}}{\epsilon_{k}-1})\frac{{c_{k}}}{\phi_{k}A_{k}}\quad where\quad\phi_{k}=(\int_{\Omega_{k}}\phi_{k}(\omega)^{\epsilon_{k}-1}d\omega)^{\frac{{1}}{\epsilon_{k}-1}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p=(\frac{{\epsilon_{k}}}{\epsilon_{k}-1})\frac{{1}}{\phi}\quad where\quad\phi=(\sum_{k}(\frac{{A_{k}\phi_{k}}}{c_{k}}))^{\frac{{1}}{\sigma-1}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Demand and Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the price function from supply and plugging it in the demand
 function, we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $q_{k}(\omega)=(\frac{{\phi_{k}(\omega)}}{\phi_{k}})^{\epsilon_{k}}(\frac{{\phi_{k}}}{\phi})^{\sigma}q$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

If we plug this and the price function in the profit function, we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{k}(\omega)=(\frac{{1}}{\epsilon_{k}})(\frac{{c_{k}}}{A_{k}})(\frac{{\phi_{k}(\omega)}}{\phi_{k}})^{\epsilon-1}(\frac{{\phi_{k}}}{\phi})^{\sigma-1}X,\qquad where\qquad X=p\times q$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Produce crop k or k'?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider there are 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\{1,...,K\}$
\end_inset

 crops in Brazil, and they are ordered such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{k=1}$
\end_inset

 is the highest and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{k=K}$
\end_inset

 is the lowest.
 Also assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<\epsilon_{k},\forall k$
\end_inset

.
 Farmer with productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 should be indifferent between producing crops 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{k=1}(\omega)=\Pi_{k=2}(\omega).$
\end_inset

 This happens at threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{*}$
\end_inset

, which is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{*}=((\frac{{A_{k=1}}}{A_{k=2}})(\frac{{c_{k=2}}}{c_{k=1}})(\frac{{\phi_{k'}^{\sigma-\epsilon_{k=2}}}}{\phi_{k}^{\sigma-\epsilon_{k=1}}}))^{\frac{{1}}{\epsilon_{k=1}-\epsilon_{k=2}}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

All farmers with productivity above 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{*}$
\end_inset

 for sure produce crop 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

.
 Something I'm not sure here is if all farmers with productivity above 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{*}$
\end_inset

 only produce crop 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 or other crops too, since we could do the same analysis with respect to
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=3$
\end_inset

 and so on.
 Let's maintain the analysis between these two crops.
 Notice that under our parametrization, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{d\phi^{*}}}{d\phi_{k}}>0$
\end_inset

 so selection to produce crop 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 is tougher when aggregate productivity for that crop is higher.
 This is the higher competition effect we expect to happen.
\end_layout

\end_body
